This shows that we can take
  \begin {array}{rcl|rcl|rcl}     f &\in & A_{\text {right}} & g &\in & M & p &\in & F_{\text {inner}} \\     f &\in & A_{\text {left}} & g &\in & M & p &\in & F_{\text {left}} \\     f &\in & M & g &\in & A_{\text {left}} & p &\in & F_{\text {inner}} \\     f &\in & M & g &\in & A_{\text {right}} & p &\in & F_{\text {right}} \\   \end {array}
  in the equivalences above.
